00:23:04,258 --> 00:23:07,552
- Things change.
- So I see.

241
00:23:07,636 --> 00:23:10,722
- My name's Teddy.
- I guess I've told you about my condition.

242
00:23:10,806 --> 00:23:14,809
Only every time I see you.
Come on, I'll buy you lunch.

243
00:23:20,441 --> 00:23:22,692
- Have I told you about Sammy Jankis?
- Yeah.

244
00:23:22,777 --> 00:23:27,322
I'm sick of hearing about the guy.
What about John G? You think he's still here?

245
00:23:27,406 --> 00:23:29,657
- Who?
- Johnny G., the guy you're looking for.

246
00:23:29,742 --> 00:23:32,327
- That's why you haven't left town, am I right?
- Maybe.

247
00:23:32,411 --> 00:23:35,705
- Leonard, look. You have to be very careful.
- Why?

248
00:23:35,790 --> 00:23:39,209
The other day you mentioned that maybe
somebody was trying to set you up...

249
00:23:39,293 --> 00:23:41,044
get you to kill the wrong guy.

250
00:23:41,128 --> 00:23:44,214
I go on facts, not recommendations,
but thank you.

251
00:23:44,298 --> 00:23:47,342
Lenny, you can't trust a man's life
to your little notes and pictures.

252
00:23:47,426 --> 00:23:50,220
- Why not?
- Because your notes could be unreliable.

253
00:23:50,304 --> 00:23:51,971
- Memory's unreliable.
- Oh, please!

254
00:23:52,056 --> 00:23:54,390
No, really. Memory's not perfect.
It's not even that good.

255
00:23:54,475 --> 00:23:58,019
Ask the police.
Eyewitness testimony is unreliable.

256
00:23:58,104 --> 00:24:01,064
The cops don't catch a killer
by sitting around remembering stuff.

257
00:24:01,148 --> 00:24:03,942
They collect facts, they make notes,
and they draw conclusions.

258
00:24:04,026 --> 00:24:06,069
Facts, not memories.

259
00:24:06,153 --> 00:24:08,613
That's how you investigate.
I know. It's what I used to do.

260
00:24:08,697 --> 00:24:12,909
Memory can change the shape ofa room.
It can change the color of a car.

261
00:24:12,993 --> 00:24:15,078
And memories can be distorted.

262
00:24:15,162 --> 00:24:17,330
They're just an interpretation.
They're not a record.

263
00:24:17,414 --> 00:24:19,499
They're irrelevant if you have the facts.

264
00:24:20,334 --> 00:24:22,293
You really want to get this guy, don't you?

265
00:24:22,378 --> 00:24:25,171
He killed my wife.
He took away my fucking memory.

266
00:24:28,092 --> 00:24:30,093
He destroyed my ability to live.

267
00:24:33,973 --> 00:24:35,014
You're living.

268
00:24:36,851 --> 00:24:38,810
Only for revenge.

269
00:24:38,894 --> 00:24:41,729
Then we'll get the bastard.
Where you staying?

270
00:24:44,525 --> 00:24:46,276
The Discount Inn.

271
00:24:47,903 --> 00:24:49,821
I don't know what room.
I haven't got my key.

272
00:24:49,905 --> 00:24:51,739
Probably left it in your room.

273
00:25:06,547 --> 00:25:09,299
Hi. I'm checked in here,
but I think I've misplaced my key.

274
00:25:10,009 --> 00:25:13,636
How you doing, Leonard?
Probably in the room, right?

275
00:25:32,323 --> 00:25:33,907
- Don't see my key anywhere.
- Shit.

276
00:25:33,991 --> 00:25:36,075
This is the wrong room.
You're in 304 now.

277
00:25:36,160 --> 00:25:38,161
- I'm sorry. I fucked up.
- This is not my room?

278
00:25:38,245 --> 00:25:39,746
No. Let's go.

279
00:25:40,873 --> 00:25:42,832
Why is this my handwriting?

280
00:25:46,962 --> 00:25:49,797
This was your room,
but now you're in 304.

281
00:25:49,882 --> 00:25:52,133
- When was I in here?
- Last week.

282
00:25:52,218 --> 00:25:54,677
But then I rented you
another room on top of it.

283
00:25:54,762 --> 00:25:56,888
- Why?
- Business is slow.

284
00:25:56,972 --> 00:25:59,849
I told my boss
about your condition and stuff...

285
00:25:59,934 --> 00:26:02,143
and he said,
"Try and rent him another room."

286
00:26:02,228 --> 00:26:04,270
How many rooms am I checked
into in this shit-hole?

287
00:26:04,355 --> 00:26:06,814
Just two, so far.

288
00:26:08,442 --> 00:26:10,568
At least you're being honest
about ripping me off.

289
00:26:10,653 --> 00:26:13,196
You're not gonna remember anyway.

290
00:26:13,280 --> 00:26:15,198
You don't have to be that honest, Burt.

291
00:26:15,282 --> 00:26:18,910
Leonard, always get a receipt.

292
00:26:18,994 --> 00:26:21,204
Yeah. I'm gonna write that down.

293
00:26:23,666 --> 00:26:25,750
- What time is it?
- Quarter to 1:00.

294
00:26:29,380 --> 00:26:30,505
Your room's...

295
00:26:43,310 --> 00:26:45,353
- Natalie?
- You don't remember me.

296
00:26:45,980 --> 00:26:48,606
I'd just become an investigator
when I came across Sammy.

297
00:26:48,691 --> 00:26:52,402
Mr. Samuel R. Jankis. Strangest case ever.

298
00:26:52,486 --> 00:26:55,280
You know, the guy's a 58-year-old
semiretired accountant.

299
00:26:55,364 --> 00:26:58,032
He and his wife had been in this car accident.
Nothing too serious.

300
00:26:58,117 --> 00:27:01,327
<i>But he's acting funny.
He can't get a handle on what's going on.

301
00:27:02,788 --> 00:27:05,581
<i>The doctors find some possible damage
to the hippocampus.

302
00:27:05,666 --> 00:27:10,211
<i>Nothing conclusive, but Sammy can't remember
anything for more than a couple of minutes.

303
00:27:10,296 --> 00:27:13,047
<i>Can't work, can't do shit.
The medical bills pile up.

304
00:27:13,132 --> 00:27:15,842
<i>His wife calls the insurance company,
and I get sent in.

305
00:27:16,427 --> 00:27:20,805
<i>Now, this is my first big claims investigation,
so I really check into it.

306
00:27:21,473 --> 00:27:26,102
<i>Sammy can think just fine,
but he can't make any new memories.

307
00:27:26,186 --> 00:27:28,521
<i>He could only remember things
for a couple of minutes.

308
00:27:28,605 --> 00:27:30,315
- This is Mr. Shelby.
<i>- He'd watch TV...

309
00:27:30,399 --> 00:27:32,734
<i>but anything longer than
a couple of minutes was too confusing.

310
00:27:32,818 --> 00:27:36,654
<i>He couldn't remember how it began.
He liked commercials. They were short.

311
00:27:36,739 --> 00:27:38,823
Sammy. It's time for my shot.

312
00:27:38,907 --> 00:27:41,784
<i>The crazy part was that this guy...

313
00:27:41,869 --> 00:27:45,079
<i>who couldn't even follow the plot
of Green Acres anymore...

314
00:27:45,164 --> 00:27:47,248
<i>could do the most complicated things...

315
00:27:48,334 --> 00:27:50,710
<i>as long as he learned them
before the accident...

316
00:27:52,046 --> 00:27:54,297
<i>and as long as he kept his mind
on what he was doing.

317
00:27:54,381 --> 00:27:56,132
Be gentle.

318
00:27:56,216 --> 00:28:00,511
<i>The doctors assure me there's a real condition
called anterograde memory loss...

319
00:28:00,596 --> 00:28:02,555
<i>or short-term memory loss.

320
00:28:02,639 --> 00:28:04,640
<i>It's rare, but legit.

321
00:28:06,393 --> 00:28:08,394
<i>But every time I see him...

322
00:28:09,229 --> 00:28:11,147
<i>I catch this look...

323
00:28:11,231 --> 00:28:14,817
<i>this slight look of recognition.

324
00:28:15,444 --> 00:28:17,737
<i>But he says he can't remember me at all.

325
00:28:17,821 --> 00:28:19,947
Sammy, it's okay. I got it. I got it.

326
00:28:20,741 --> 00:28:22,867
- Hi, Mr. Shelby.
- Hi, Mrs. Jankis.

327
00:28:22,951 --> 00:28:26,913
<i>I can read people,
and I'm thinking: Bad actor.

328
00:28:27,623 --> 00:28:30,500
So now I'm suspicious, and I order more tests.

329
00:28:33,712 --> 00:28:35,088
Awake.

330
00:28:37,007 --> 00:28:38,800
Where am I?

331
00:28:42,679 --> 00:28:44,430
Somebody's bedroom.

332
00:28:46,141 --> 00:28:48,101
It must be her room.

333
00:28:49,520 --> 00:28:51,229
But who is she?

334
00:28:59,488 --> 00:29:01,447
It's only me.

335
00:29:03,700 --> 00:29:06,661
- Did you sleep okay?
- Yeah. You?

336
00:29:08,455 --> 00:29:12,125
Oh, shit. I gotta be someplace.

337
00:29:16,797 --> 00:29:19,632
- It's pretty weird.
- It's useful.

338
00:29:20,676 --> 00:29:22,635
You never write a phone number on your hand?

339
00:29:23,262 --> 00:29:28,182
I should be able to talk to my friend
today about the license plate.

340
00:29:28,267 --> 00:29:32,103
- Yeah, the license plate.
- John G.'s license plate.

341
00:29:35,315 --> 00:29:37,233
You have it tattooed on your thigh.

342
00:29:55,502 --> 00:29:57,086
"Natalie."

343
00:29:59,673 --> 00:30:01,674
"She has also lost someone.

344
00:30:01,758 --> 00:30:03,676
She will help you out of pity."

345
00:30:08,932 --> 00:30:10,850
If it's registered in this state...

346
00:30:10,934 --> 00:30:13,936
it should only take a couple seconds
to pull up his license and registration.

347
00:30:14,021 --> 00:30:15,813
I'll call you as soon as I talk to him.

348
00:30:15,898 --> 00:30:19,901
Do you think we could just arrange a meeting now?
I'm not too good on the phone.

349
00:30:28,494 --> 00:30:30,495
It's great that you...

350
00:30:31,997 --> 00:30:36,083
that you're helping me like this.

351
00:30:36,168 --> 00:30:39,670
I'm helping you because you helped me.

352
00:30:51,767 --> 00:30:55,645
So next time you see me,
will you remember me?

353
00:31:12,746 --> 00:31:14,664
I think you will.

354
00:31:16,416 --> 00:31:18,125
I'm sorry.

355
00:31:21,255 --> 00:31:24,090
Lenny, before you go,
could I have my shirt back, please?

356
00:31:39,398 --> 00:31:43,317
Yo, Lenny! I thought you split for good.

357
00:31:43,402 --> 00:31:45,778
Sammy couldn't pick up any new skills at all.

358
00:31:46,613 --> 00:31:50,199
But I find something
in my research: Conditioning.

359
00:31:50,284 --> 00:31:53,286
Sammy should still be able to learn
through repetition.

360
00:31:53,370 --> 00:31:56,789
It's how you learn stuff like riding a bike.
You just get better through practice.

361
00:31:56,873 --> 00:31:59,375
It's a completely different part ofthe brain
from the short-term memory.

362
00:31:59,459 --> 00:32:02,545
So I had the doctors test
Sammy's response to conditioning.

363
00:32:02,629 --> 00:32:04,797
Just pick up any three objects.

364
00:32:04,881 --> 00:32:07,049
That's a test?

365
00:32:07,134 --> 00:32:09,719
Where were you guys when I did my CPA?

366
00:32:10,804 --> 00:32:11,971
Sorry.

367
00:32:16,018 --> 00:32:17,768
Ow! What the fuck?

368
00:32:17,853 --> 00:32:21,063
- It's a test, Sammy.
- Test this, you fucking quack.

369
00:32:22,399 --> 00:32:24,567
<i>Some ofthe objects were electrified.

370
00:32:24,651 --> 00:32:27,028
<i>They'd give him a small shock.
They kept repeating the test...

371
00:32:27,112 --> 00:32:29,071
always with the same objects electrified.

372
00:32:29,156 --> 00:32:32,742
The point was to see if Sammy could learn
to avoid the electrified objects...

373
00:32:32,826 --> 00:32:34,827
not by memory, but by instinct.

374
00:32:56,016 --> 00:32:58,517
Natalie, right? Who the fuck is Dodd?

375
00:33:02,147 --> 00:33:05,232
- Guess I don't have to worry about him anymore.
- What the fuck have you got me into?

376
00:33:05,317 --> 00:33:06,817
Come inside.

377
00:33:10,030 --> 00:33:12,990
- Who is he?
- Calm down. Okay?

378
00:33:13,075 --> 00:33:16,577
This is my problem. You offered to help.
It has nothing to do with your investigation.

379
00:33:16,662 --> 00:33:18,162
How did you get me into this?

380
00:33:18,246 --> 00:33:20,289
You offered to help when you saw
what he did to my face.

381
00:33:20,374 --> 00:33:23,959
- How do I know he did that to your face?
- Because I came straight to you after he did it.

382
00:33:24,044 --> 00:33:26,295
I showed you what he did,
and I asked you to help me.

383
00:33:26,380 --> 00:33:28,339
- And I just take your word?
- Yeah.

384
00:33:29,800 --> 00:33:31,717
Something doesn't feel right.

385
00:33:31,802 --> 00:33:34,345
I think someone's fucking with me,
trying to get me to kill the wrong guy.

386
00:33:34,429 --> 00:33:35,846
- Did you?
- What?

387
00:33:35,931 --> 00:33:38,349
- Kill him?
- Of course not!

388
00:33:38,433 --> 00:33:39,475
Hey.

389
00:33:39,559 --> 00:33:41,394
Sit down, okay? Sit.

390
00:33:42,229 --> 00:33:45,314
This has nothing to do with you.

391
00:33:45,399 --> 00:33:47,775
You helped me out, and I'm grateful.

392
00:33:48,735 --> 00:33:50,569
You have to burn them.

393
00:33:52,989 --> 00:33:56,158
Leonard, you decided to help me.
Trust yourself.

394
00:33:56,243 --> 00:33:58,244
Trust your own judgment.
You can question everything.

395
00:33:58,328 --> 00:34:02,081
- You can never know anything for sure.
- There are things you know for sure.

396
00:34:02,165 --> 00:34:03,290
Such as?

397
00:34:05,168 --> 00:34:07,586
I know what that's gonna sound like
when I knock on it.

398
00:34:08,296 --> 00:34:10,673
I know what that's gonna
feel like when I pick it up.

399
00:34:10,757 --> 00:34:14,427
See? Certainties. It's the kind
of memory you take for granted.

400
00:34:15,929 --> 00:34:18,431
You know, I can remember so much.

401
00:34:20,434 --> 00:34:23,728
The feel ofthe world... and her.

402
00:34:30,610 --> 00:34:32,153
She's gone.

403
00:34:32,237 --> 00:34:36,198
And the present is trivia,
which I scribble down as fucking notes!

404
00:34:36,283 --> 00:34:39,201
Hey. Come on. Try and relax. Come on.

405
00:34:39,286 --> 00:34:41,620
It's not easy for me to relax, you know?

406
00:34:42,414 --> 00:34:44,373
Come on. Take your jacket off.

407
00:34:44,958 --> 00:34:47,001
Now. Come on.

408
00:34:48,962 --> 00:34:50,546
Hey.

409
00:34:52,257 --> 00:34:54,425
Didn't think you were the type.

410
00:35:02,350 --> 00:35:03,476
It's backwards.

411
00:35:05,187 --> 00:35:06,228
Come here.

412
00:35:06,813 --> 00:35:07,980
Come here.

413
00:35:29,795 --> 00:35:31,921
What about here?

414
00:35:33,173 --> 00:35:35,674
Maybe it's for when I find him.

415
00:35:38,428 --> 00:35:40,846
I've lost somebody too.

416
00:35:42,849 --> 00:35:44,266
I'm sorry.

417
00:35:44,351 --> 00:35:46,560
His name was Jimmy.

418
00:35:46,645 --> 00:35:49,688
- What happened to him?
- He went to meet somebody.

419
00:35:49,773 --> 00:35:51,732
He never came back.

420
00:35:52,734 --> 00:35:55,486
- Who did he go to meet?
- A guy called Teddy.

421
00:35:56,780 --> 00:35:58,781
What do the police think?

422
00:35:58,865 --> 00:36:01,742
They don't look too hard for guys like Jimmy.

423
00:36:03,411 --> 00:36:07,373
When you find this guy, this John G...

424
00:36:08,500 --> 00:36:10,417
what are you gonna do?

425
00:36:11,920 --> 00:36:14,088
I'm gonna kill him.

426
00:36:15,632 --> 00:36:17,675
Maybe I can help you find him.

427
00:36:22,681 --> 00:36:25,182
I don't even know how long she's been gone.

428
00:36:29,563 --> 00:36:32,565
It's like I've woken up in bed
and she's not here...

429
00:36:35,068 --> 00:36:37,444
because she's gone to
the bathroom or something.

430
00:36:42,409 --> 00:36:44,493
But somehow I just...

431
00:36:45,245 --> 00:36:48,539
I just know she's never gonna come back to bed.

432
00:36:54,087 --> 00:36:59,592
If I could just reach over
and touch her side ofthe bed...

433
00:37:01,261 --> 00:37:03,387
I would know that it was cold.

434
00:37:06,558 --> 00:37:08,517
But I can't.

435
00:37:12,647 --> 00:37:14,440
I know I can't have her back.

436
00:37:16,151 --> 00:37:20,154
But I don't want to wake up
in the morning thinking she's still here.

437
00:37:21,698 --> 00:37:26,076
I lie here not knowing
how long I've been alone.

438
00:37:34,628 --> 00:37:36,921
How can I heal?

439
00:37:39,382 --> 00:37:44,470
How am I supposed to heal
if I can't... feel time?

440
00:38:57,335 --> 00:38:59,795
"She has also lost someone.

441
00:39:00,338 --> 00:39:02,339
She will help you out of pity."

442
00:39:27,699 --> 00:39:29,616
They kept testing Sammy for months...

443
00:39:29,701 --> 00:39:32,494
always with the same objects
carrying the electrical charge.

444
00:39:33,830 --> 00:39:35,330
Ow! What the fuck?

445
00:39:35,415 --> 00:39:37,833
- It's a test, Sammy.
- Test this, you fucking quack!

446
00:39:37,917 --> 00:39:40,627
Even with total short-term memory loss...

447
00:39:40,712 --> 00:39:43,464
<i>Sammy should have learned to instinctively stop
picking up the wrong objects.

448
00:39:43,548 --> 00:39:47,593
<i>All the previous cases responded to conditioning.
Sammy didn't respond at all.

449
00:39:47,677 --> 00:39:51,263
<i>It was enough to suggest that his condition
was psychological, not physical.

450
00:39:51,347 --> 00:39:54,808
We turned down his claim on the grounds
that he wasn't covered for mental illness.

451
00:39:55,769 --> 00:39:58,604
His wife got stuck with the bills,
and I got a big promotion.

452
00:40:00,482 --> 00:40:03,984
Conditioning didn't work for Sammy,
so he became helpless.

453
00:40:04,069 --> 00:40:05,986
But it works for me.

454
00:40:06,529 --> 00:40:08,447
I live the way Sammy couldn't.

455
00:40:08,531 --> 00:40:10,949
Habit and routine make my life possible.

456
00:40:11,034 --> 00:40:13,952
Conditioning. Acting on instinct.

457
00:40:22,712 --> 00:40:23,962
Awake.

458
00:40:25,715 --> 00:40:27,216
Where am I?

459
00:40:28,885 --> 00:40:30,427
Motel room.

460
00:40:37,018 --> 00:40:39,561
Some anonymous motel room.

461
00:40:43,066 --> 00:40:46,485
Nothing in the drawers,
but I'll take a look anyway.

462
00:40:47,153 --> 00:40:50,030
Nothing except the Gideon Bible.

463
00:41:04,671 --> 00:41:06,255
Lenny! Open up!

464
00:41:08,424 --> 00:41:10,050
Just a minute.

465
00:41:10,135 --> 00:41:11,677
Open the door.

466
00:41:13,930 --> 00:41:15,013
Lenny.

467
00:41:17,809 --> 00:41:19,768
Open the door.

468
00:41:23,523 --> 00:41:24,773
Come on!

469
00:41:26,651 --> 00:41:28,360
Hi, Teddy.

470
00:41:28,444 --> 00:41:30,696
Finished playing with yourself, Lenny?

471
00:41:42,876 --> 00:41:44,960
I get it.

472
00:41:45,044 --> 00:41:46,503
Amorous neighbors.

473
00:41:46,588 --> 00:41:48,046
What are you doing here?

474
00:41:48,840 --> 00:41:51,842
You called me. You said you needed my help.

475
00:41:51,926 --> 00:41:55,470
I've had more rewarding
friendships than this one.

476
00:41:55,555 --> 00:41:58,891
Although I do get to keep
telling the same jokes.

477
00:41:59,559 --> 00:42:01,643
What the fuck is that?

478
00:42:07,150 --> 00:42:09,151
- Who the fuck is that?
- You don't know him?

479
00:42:09,235 --> 00:42:10,861
No! Should I?

480
00:42:10,945 --> 00:42:12,571
Wait a minute.

481
00:42:12,655 --> 00:42:15,115
- Is that John G?
- I don't think so.

482
00:42:15,200 --> 00:42:18,493
- You don't think so? You didn't write it down?
- I might've fallen asleep before I did.

483
00:42:18,578 --> 00:42:20,579
For Christ's sakes!

484
00:42:21,873 --> 00:42:23,415
Ask him.

485
00:42:27,503 --> 00:42:29,046
What's your name?

486
00:42:29,130 --> 00:42:30,130
Your name.

487
00:42:30,715 --> 00:42:32,549
- Dodd.
- Who did this to you?

488
00:42:32,634 --> 00:42:35,219
- What?
- Who did this to you?

489
00:42:35,303 --> 00:42:36,803
You did.

490
00:42:40,058 --> 00:42:43,310
- I'm not gonna help you kill that guy.
- No, just let me think for a minute.

491
00:42:49,108 --> 00:42:51,526
Okay, Natalie. Who's Natalie?

492
00:42:51,611 --> 00:42:53,070
- Natalie who?
- Why?

493
00:42:53,154 --> 00:42:56,240
- Maybe I know her.
- Look. We gotta get him out of here.

494
00:42:57,158 --> 00:42:58,784
All right, all right.

495
00:42:59,911 --> 00:43:01,870
He's gotta have a car, right?

496
00:43:01,955 --> 00:43:05,540
We take him down to his car, tell him to get
the fuck out oftown or we're gonna kill him.

497
00:43:05,625 --> 00:43:07,709
We can't walk him out of here
tied up and bleeding.

498
00:43:07,794 --> 00:43:10,254
- How the fuck did you get him up here?
- I don't know.

499
00:43:10,338 --> 00:43:12,297
You don't know.

500
00:43:14,467 --> 00:43:16,385
Yes, I do. This is not my room.

501
00:43:16,469 --> 00:43:18,262
It must be his room. Great! Let's go.

502
00:43:18,346 --> 00:43:20,305
- No, no. We can't just leave him here.
- Why not?

503
00:43:20,390 --> 00:43:24,935
Because the maid's gonna walk in.
She'll see him, call the cops. He can ID us.

504
00:43:26,813 --> 00:43:28,647
Okay. We untie him...

505
00:43:28,731 --> 00:43:31,608
we clean him up, and we march him
out of here with a gun in his back.

506
00:43:31,693 --> 00:43:33,652
A gun. Why would I have a gun?

507
00:43:35,154 --> 00:43:38,490
It must be his. I don't think
they'd let someone like me carry a gun.

508
00:43:40,034 --> 00:43:41,326
Fucking hope not.

509
00:43:48,668 --> 00:43:50,168
Which one?

510
00:43:53,172 --> 00:43:55,716
We should probably steal his car.
You know, teach him a lesson.

511
00:43:55,800 --> 00:43:56,758
Shut up.

512
00:43:56,843 --> 00:43:59,261
That's all right for you to say.
You're the one with the Jag.

513
00:43:59,345 --> 00:44:02,222
Get in.
I'm gonna ride with him. You follow us.

514
00:44:02,307 --> 00:44:04,224
Give me your keys.

515
00:44:04,309 --> 00:44:06,518
Take your own car.

516
00:44:34,464 --> 00:44:37,507
- So was he scared?
- Yeah. I think it was your sinister mustache.

517
00:44:37,592 --> 00:44:40,302
Fuck you. You should have stolen his car.

518
00:44:40,386 --> 00:44:43,430
- Why? What's wrong with this one?
- Nothing. You want to trade?

519
00:44:46,768 --> 00:44:48,852
So what do you do now?

520
00:44:48,936 --> 00:44:51,396
I'm going to find out
what the fuck that was all about.

521
00:44:58,988 --> 00:45:01,406
Natalie, right? Who the fuck is Dodd?

522
00:45:04,035 --> 00:45:07,079
Sammy's wife was crippled
by the cost ofsupporting him...

523
00:45:07,163 --> 00:45:09,247
and fighting the company's decision.

524
00:45:11,125 --> 00:45:13,418
But it wasn't the money that got to her.

525
00:45:13,503 --> 00:45:16,505
<i>- I never said that Sammy was faking.</i>
- Listen. I have an idea.

526
00:45:16,589 --> 00:45:18,215
Sammy, I have an idea.

527
00:45:18,299 --> 00:45:20,967
<i>Just that his problem was mental, not physical.

528
00:45:21,052 --> 00:45:24,304
I want you to have a pen in your pocket, okay?

529
00:45:24,389 --> 00:45:26,932
<i>- But she couldn't understand.</i>
- You're gonna have a pad in your pocket.

530
00:45:27,016 --> 00:45:29,017
- I did something wrong?
- You did something wrong!

531
00:45:29,102 --> 00:45:32,229
We're gonna deal with it.
We're gonna try harder.

532
00:45:32,313 --> 00:45:34,439
<i>She looks into his eyes
and sees the same person.

533
00:45:34,524 --> 00:45:37,651
<i>If it's not a physical problem,
he should just snap out of it.

534
00:45:37,735 --> 00:45:39,444
- Ellen called!
- Ellen called?

535
00:45:40,613 --> 00:45:44,157
- Ellen can't come today! Ellen can't come!
- Okay. I'm sorry!

536
00:45:44,242 --> 00:45:47,369
- I'm sorry. I'm trying. I'm sorry.
- Try harder!

537
00:45:51,124 --> 00:45:55,252
So good old Leonard Shelby from the insurance
company gives her the seed ofdoubt...

538
00:45:55,837 --> 00:45:57,963
just like he gave it to the doctors.

539
00:45:58,756 --> 00:46:01,466
But I never said that he was faking.
I never said that.

540
00:46:07,807 --> 00:46:10,183
I don't feel drunk.

541
00:47:22,381 --> 00:47:23,882
- Hello?
- Shit.

542
00:47:23,966 --> 00:47:25,383
Housekeeping.

543
00:47:25,468 --> 00:47:27,552
- Not right now.
- I'm sorry.

544
00:47:50,868 --> 00:47:51,743
Okay.

545
00:47:56,457 --> 00:48:00,585
"Dodd. Put him onto Teddy
orjust get rid of him for Natalie."

546
00:48:06,634 --> 00:48:07,759
Dodd.

547
00:48:12,932 --> 00:48:16,309
Get rid of him. Ask Natalie.

548
00:48:18,563 --> 00:48:19,813
Teddy, Teddy.

549
00:48:31,242 --> 00:48:33,493
<i>Leave your number.
You know what to do.

550
00:48:33,578 --> 00:48:35,745
Yeah. This is a message for Teddy.

551
00:48:35,830 --> 00:48:37,872
I'm at the Mountcrest Inn
of Fifth Street, room six.

552
00:48:37,957 --> 00:48:40,959
I need you to come over
as soon as you get this. It's important.

553
00:48:41,043 --> 00:48:43,295
This is Leonard. Thanks. Bye.

554
00:48:47,592 --> 00:48:49,092
Fuck.

555
00:48:58,477 --> 00:49:02,147
What Mrs. Jankis didn't understand was
that you can't bully someone into remembering.

556
00:49:02,231 --> 00:49:04,232
The more pressure you're under,
the harder it gets.

557
00:49:06,986 --> 00:49:08,987
Then call me back?

558
00:49:30,926 --> 00:49:32,719
Okay. What am I doing?

559
00:49:35,056 --> 00:49:36,681
I'm chasing this guy.

560
00:49:39,268 --> 00:49:41,936
No. He's chasing me.

561
00:50:04,752 --> 00:50:06,378
Fuck.

562
00:50:09,799 --> 00:50:12,092
"Dodd. White guy.

563
00:50:12,176 --> 00:50:14,135
Mountcrest Inn on Fifth Street."

564
00:50:15,096 --> 00:50:17,764
I'll get the jump on you, you fucker.

565
00:50:54,301 --> 00:50:55,760
Fuck.

566
00:50:58,431 --> 00:50:59,764
Sorry.

567
00:51:33,299 --> 00:51:35,300
I need a weapon.

568
00:51:38,554 --> 00:51:39,721
This'll do.

569
00:52:03,454 --> 00:52:05,872
I don't feel drunk.

570
00:52:47,915 --> 00:52:49,541
Do I know this guy?

571
00:52:51,001 --> 00:52:52,544
He seems to know me.

572
00:52:57,383 --> 00:52:58,800
What the fuck?

573
00:53:12,398 --> 00:53:14,566
- I like your car.
- Thank you.

574
00:53:14,650 --> 00:53:16,651
- Where'd you get it?
- Are you interested in buying one?

575
00:53:17,278 --> 00:53:19,195
I haven't made a strong enough
impression on you?

576
00:53:19,280 --> 00:53:21,281
I wouldn't be too hard on yourself.

577
00:53:32,001 --> 00:53:33,918
Okay. What am I doing?

578
00:53:44,597 --> 00:53:46,306
Who is this?

579
00:55:04,927 --> 00:55:06,844
Ouch. Cut it out.

580
00:55:38,627 --> 00:55:41,796
- How can you read that again?
- It's good.

581
00:55:43,048 --> 00:55:44,924
Yeah, but you've read it,
like, a thousand times.

582
00:55:45,009 --> 00:55:46,592
I enjoy it.

583
00:55:47,761 --> 00:55:50,596
I always thought the pleasure of a book
was in wanting to know what happens next.

584
00:55:50,681 --> 00:55:52,390
Don't be a prick.

585
00:55:52,474 --> 00:55:55,059
I'm not reading it to annoy you. I enjoy it.

586
00:55:56,186 --> 00:55:58,688
Just let me read, please.

587
00:56:09,533 --> 00:56:11,909
Probably tried this before.

588
00:56:14,038 --> 00:56:16,873
Probably burned truckloads of your stuff.

589
00:56:19,418 --> 00:56:21,419
Can't remember to forget you.

590
00:56:39,772 --> 00:56:40,813
Yeah.

591
00:56:41,398 --> 00:56:42,607
Uh-huh.

592
00:56:44,443 --> 00:56:47,570
Sir, that'd certainly be in keeping
with some of my own discoveries.

593
00:56:48,155 --> 00:56:51,532
I was hoping for a little more on the drugs angle.
Can you hang on a sec?

594
00:57:00,125 --> 00:57:03,377
The police report mentioned
the drugs found in the car outside my house.

595
00:57:03,462 --> 00:57:05,546
The car was stolen,
but his prints were all over it.

596
00:57:05,631 --> 00:57:08,341
I got friends in the department.
They gave me a copy of it.

597
00:57:08,425 --> 00:57:10,718
I dealt with the police a lot
in my insurancejob.

598
00:57:10,803 --> 00:57:14,889
With my condition, it's really tough.
I can't keep it all in mind at once.

599
00:57:14,973 --> 00:57:18,226
I have to summarize the different sections.
And there's pages missing.

600
00:57:18,310 --> 00:57:20,478
I guess I've been trying to log them all.

601
00:57:20,562 --> 00:57:22,814
I don't know why these are crossed out.

602
00:57:22,898 --> 00:57:24,816
But they weren't even looking for John G.

603
00:57:24,900 --> 00:57:27,652
The stuffthey found in the car fit in with
what they believed had happened...

604
00:57:27,736 --> 00:57:29,654
so they didn't chase any of it up.

605
00:58:05,774 --> 00:58:06,858
Honey.

606
00:58:09,361 --> 00:58:11,154
Honey, it's late.

607
00:58:33,385 --> 00:58:35,303
Everything okay?

608
00:58:52,946 --> 00:58:54,405
You okay in there?

609
00:58:57,910 --> 00:58:59,619
Was it good foryou?

610
00:59:01,830 --> 00:59:04,749
What? Was I supposed to lock the door?

611
00:59:05,667 --> 00:59:06,751
No.

612
00:59:09,171 --> 00:59:11,088
I'd like you to leave now.

613
00:59:32,110 --> 00:59:35,154
There's something about the drugs stashed
in the car that doesn't ring true for me.

614
00:59:35,822 --> 00:59:37,740
Because the police claim
the guy was an addict...

615
00:59:37,824 --> 00:59:39,825
needing money to score,
which I think is bullshit...

616
00:59:39,910 --> 00:59:43,162
'cause he's not gonna go breaking into places
while he's still got a stash that big.

617
00:59:44,122 --> 00:59:46,791
I think John G. Left it there
or planted it there.

618
00:59:48,627 --> 00:59:50,628
How do you know that?

619
00:59:52,089 --> 00:59:54,090
Shit. That's true. It fits.

620
00:59:54,800 --> 00:59:56,759
So he's a dealer.

621
00:59:57,427 --> 00:59:59,345
Hang on a sec.

622
01:00:09,481 --> 01:00:11,482
Now we're getting somewhere.

623
01:00:11,566 --> 01:00:13,150
"Discount Inn."

624
01:01:07,122 --> 01:01:09,332
Yeah, okay. Blonde's fine.

625
01:01:11,710 --> 01:01:13,836
That's what they say.

626
01:01:13,920 --> 01:01:16,047
The Discount Inn. 304.

627
01:01:17,049 --> 01:01:18,090
Leonard.

628
01:01:19,509 --> 01:01:20,926
What then?

629
01:01:21,511 --> 01:01:24,221
We just go to bed.
You wait for me to fall asleep.

630
01:01:24,306 --> 01:01:26,390
You go into the bathroom and you slam the door.

631
01:01:26,475 --> 01:01:29,018
- Slam it?
- Yeah. Loud enough to wake me up.

632
01:01:29,102 --> 01:01:31,062
- And that's it?
- That's it.

633
01:01:33,857 --> 01:01:36,901
First I just need you to put
these things around the room.

634
01:01:39,946 --> 01:01:43,074
Just pretend they're your things
and that this is your bedroom.

635
01:01:54,878 --> 01:01:59,757
- Should I wear it?
- No. Just like you took it off or something.

636
01:02:02,719 --> 01:02:05,137
I don't want you to use it. I'm sorry.

637
01:02:06,848 --> 01:02:08,933
I just mean put them
around the room...

638
01:02:09,017 --> 01:02:11,602
as ifthey were your things.

639
01:02:16,108 --> 01:02:18,109
Whatever gets you off.

640
01:02:42,509 --> 01:02:44,635
I can't blame the cops
for not taking me seriously.

641
01:02:44,719 --> 01:02:47,054
This is a difficult condition
for people to understand.

642
01:02:47,139 --> 01:02:50,391
Look at Sammy Jankis.
His own wife couldn't deal with it.

643
01:02:50,475 --> 01:02:53,018
I told you about how she tried
to get him to snap out of it.

644
01:02:53,103 --> 01:02:56,439
Eventually she came to see me at the office.
I found out all kinds of shit.

645
01:02:56,940 --> 01:02:59,400
<i>She told me about life with Sammy,
how she treated him.

646
01:02:59,484 --> 01:03:00,943
Thank you for seeing me.

647
01:03:01,027 --> 01:03:03,779
It got to the point where she'd get Sammy
to hide food all around the house.

648
01:03:03,864 --> 01:03:05,614
Then she'd stop feeding him
to see if his hunger...

649
01:03:05,699 --> 01:03:07,658
would make him remember
where he'd hidden the food.

650
01:03:09,995 --> 01:03:12,621
<i>She wasn't a cruel person.
She just wanted old Sammy back.

651
01:03:12,706 --> 01:03:16,500
Mr. Shelby, you know all about Sammy
and you've decided that he's faking.

652
01:03:16,585 --> 01:03:19,211
Mrs. Jankis, the company's position
isn't that Sammy is faking anything...

653
01:03:19,296 --> 01:03:21,213
just that his condition can't be shown to be...

654
01:03:21,298 --> 01:03:24,758
I just want to know
what your honest opinion about Sammy is.

655
01:03:24,843 --> 01:03:27,761
We shouldn't even be talking like this
while the case is still open to appeal.

656
01:03:27,846 --> 01:03:31,098
- I'm not appealing the decision.
- Then why are you here?

657
01:03:31,183 --> 01:03:33,642
Try to understand.
When I look at Sammy...

658
01:03:33,727 --> 01:03:37,188
I don't see some... vegetable.

659
01:03:37,272 --> 01:03:39,356
I see my same old Sammy.

660
01:03:41,526 --> 01:03:45,946
What do you think that's like for me to suspect
he might be imagining this whole problem...

661
01:03:46,031 --> 01:03:48,115
and that if I just could say the right thing...

662
01:03:48,200 --> 01:03:50,993
he'd snap out of it
and go back to being normal?

663
01:03:56,541 --> 01:04:00,336
If I knew that my old Sammy were truly gone...

664
01:04:00,420 --> 01:04:04,548
then I could say good-bye
and start loving this new Sammy.

665
01:04:06,551 --> 01:04:09,386
As long as I have doubt,
I can't say good-bye and move on.

666
01:04:09,471 --> 01:04:11,222
What do you want from me?

667
01:04:11,306 --> 01:04:14,475
I want you to forget the company
you work for for 30 seconds...

668
01:04:14,559 --> 01:04:18,229
and tell me if you really believe
that Sammy's faking his condition.

669
01:04:19,397 --> 01:04:23,484
I need to know... what you honestly believe.

670
01:04:28,823 --> 01:04:32,409
I believe that Sammy should be physically
capable of making new memories.

671
01:04:40,335 --> 01:04:41,418
Thank you.

672
01:04:44,089 --> 01:04:47,007
I thought I helped her. I thought
she just needed some kind of answer.

673
01:04:47,092 --> 01:04:49,093
I didn't think it was important
what the answer was...

674
01:04:49,928 --> 01:04:51,929
just that she had one to believe.

675
01:05:07,028 --> 01:05:09,863
- A car this nice you should lock.
- Who the fuck are you?

676
01:05:09,948 --> 01:05:12,283
- Teddy, your buddy.
- Prove it.

677
01:05:12,367 --> 01:05:15,995
Sammy. Remember Sammy?
You told me about Sammy!

678
01:05:17,539 --> 01:05:19,039
Geez!

679
01:05:19,124 --> 01:05:21,041
What the fuck are you doing in my car?

680
01:05:21,126 --> 01:05:23,252
What, your sense of humor went with the memory?

681
01:05:23,336 --> 01:05:26,297
- Do you even know why you're here?
- Unfinished business.

682
01:05:26,381 --> 01:05:28,757
Lenny, let me inform you.

683
01:05:28,842 --> 01:05:31,218
Your business here is very much finished.

684
01:05:31,303 --> 01:05:34,305
- You're still here because of Natalie.
- Who's Natalie?

685
01:05:34,389 --> 01:05:37,516
Schmuck, whose house do you think
you just walked out of?

686
01:05:39,894 --> 01:05:43,314
That's right. Take a look at your pictures.
I bet you got one of her.

687
01:05:45,233 --> 01:05:47,526
Nice shot, Leibovitz.

688
01:05:48,194 --> 01:05:51,363
You'll wanna make a note.
You can't trust her.

689
01:05:51,448 --> 01:05:52,823
Yeah? Why's that?

690
01:05:52,907 --> 01:05:56,160
Because by now she's taken
a look at this suit and the car...

691
01:05:56,244 --> 01:06:00,623
and she's starting to figure out ways
of turning the situation to her advantage.

692
01:06:01,583 --> 01:06:04,043
She's already got you staying
with her, for Christ's sakes.

693
01:06:04,127 --> 01:06:07,713
You can't go back in there.
Let me give you the name of a motel.

694
01:06:07,797 --> 01:06:11,675
- You're lucky I ran into you. That broad's bad news.
- What do you mean, "bad news"?

695
01:06:11,760 --> 01:06:14,053
She's involved with drugs.

696
01:06:14,137 --> 01:06:16,430
Look. These. You see these?

697
01:06:16,514 --> 01:06:18,474
This is the bar where she works.

698
01:06:18,558 --> 01:06:20,601
Her boyfriend's a drug dealer.

699
01:06:20,685 --> 01:06:23,312
She takes orders for him, arranges meets.

700
01:06:23,396 --> 01:06:26,273
He writes messages on the back of these.

701
01:06:26,358 --> 01:06:28,901
Then she slips him the answers
when she serves him his drinks.

702
01:06:28,985 --> 01:06:33,072
- Why should I care?
- Because when she gets jammed up...

703
01:06:33,156 --> 01:06:35,324
she's gonna use you to protect herself.

704
01:06:35,408 --> 01:06:36,617
From who?

705
01:06:36,701 --> 01:06:39,453
Guys are gonna wanna know
what happened to her boyfriend.

706
01:06:39,537 --> 01:06:43,082
Guys are gonna come after her.
Somebody's gotta pay, Lenny.

707
01:06:43,166 --> 01:06:46,210
Somebody always pays.
Maybe she'll make it you.

708
01:06:46,294 --> 01:06:49,797
Oh, yeah?
Maybe she'll make it you. Is that it?

709
01:06:49,881 --> 01:06:51,799
You worried that she's gonna use me against you?

710
01:06:51,883 --> 01:06:53,884
- No.
- Why not?

711
01:06:54,594 --> 01:06:57,221
Because she doesn't know who I am.

712
01:06:58,223 --> 01:07:00,766
- Why are you following me?
- Maybe I wanna help.

713
01:07:01,559 --> 01:07:04,770
She doesn't know anything about
your investigation, okay, Einstein?

714
01:07:04,854 --> 01:07:07,523
So write this down.

715
01:07:07,607 --> 01:07:12,277
When she offers to help,
it'll be for her own reasons.

716
01:07:12,362 --> 01:07:17,157
I'm not lying.
Take my pen. Write this down.

717
01:07:17,242 --> 01:07:19,410
Do not trust her.

718
01:07:26,835 --> 01:07:30,337
- There. You happy now?
- I won't be happy until you leave town.

719
01:07:30,422 --> 01:07:32,339
Why not?

720
01:07:32,424 --> 01:07:35,926
